{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01MqtFx13ARiE97YZnYteTye","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RXifZhywRKEY8JXRkqRSRq","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The keyword-frequency analyzer assigns the correct sentiment when the review contains only words from the configured positive and negative word lists.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure boundary is the analyzer's matching and threshold logic. Real failures: wrong keyword matching (case sensitivity, partial matches), incorrect threshold application, off-by-one errors in frequency counting. A Unit test passing real word list data and reviews directly to the analyzer catches these. Mocking the analyzer itself would hide logic errors, but testing the real function with test data (not mocking internals) is sufficient—no external service, OS, subprocess, or LLM non-determinism involved.","test_description":"Create a test that passes a configured word list and a review containing only positive/negative words to the analyzer. Verify the sentiment score matches the expected output. Test edge cases: mixed case words, punctuation, word boundaries, and threshold boundaries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit level is sufficient because the analyzer is deterministic, local logic. Config loading (Integration level) is a separate concern from the analyzer's correctness. The behavior focuses on 'assigns the correct sentiment', not 'loads config correctly'.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The explanation analyzer produces reasoning that references specific phrases from the original review, not generic boilerplate.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The explanation is generated by an LLM or sophisticated NLP component ('produces natural language reasoning'). Real failures: LLM ignores instructions and returns generic templates, loses specific phrase references, or produces unrelated reasoning. Mocking the LLM would always return valid text with phrase references, hiding the real failure where a live LLM sometimes fails to follow instructions. The correctness depends on non-deterministic LLM behavior—outcomes vary across runs even with identical inputs. Only testing with the real LLM can catch failures.","test_description":"Test the explanation analyzer with real LLM calls using diverse reviews. For each review, verify the explanation contains specific phrases/quotes from the input (not generic templates like 'The review expresses a positive sentiment'). Use semantic/string matching to ensure phrase references. Run multiple times if possible to catch non-deterministic failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic level is mandatory because the failure is in real LLM behavior. Integration/Unit tests with mocked LLM would create false confidence by always returning reference-containing text.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a review contains mixed signals (both positive and negative keywords), the sentiment score reflects the configured tie-breaking rule.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure boundary is the tie-breaking logic in the analyzer. Real failures: wrong operator applied (e.g., 'max' instead of 'min'), off-by-one in thresholds, incorrect rule precedence. A Unit test with mixed-signal reviews and configurable tie-breaking rules can catch these. The logic is deterministic and local. Mocking the rule evaluation would hide the failure, but testing the real analyzer with different tie-breaking configurations catches it.","test_description":"Test the analyzer with reviews containing equal counts of positive and negative keywords. Parameterize the test with different tie-breaking rules (first-wins, count-weighted, user-history, etc.). Verify each returns the expected sentiment per the rule. Test boundary conditions: equal counts, slight imbalance, multiple rule invocations in sequence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit level is sufficient because tie-breaking is deterministic local logic. Testing with real analyzer + test data (not mocked rules) catches all failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.65,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The explanation for a sarcastic review (e.g., 'Great, another broken feature') correctly identifies the negative intent despite positive surface words.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Sarcasm detection requires contextual language understanding beyond keyword matching. Real failures: LLM misses sarcasm and treats 'Great' as positive, or produces an explanation that doesn't recognize negative intent. Keyword-based approaches will fail on sarcasm (positive words + broken = ???). Mocking the explanation analyzer to always detect sarcasm hides the real failure where live LLMs sometimes miss it. The correctness depends on non-deterministic LLM behavior. Only live LLM testing catches sarcasm failures.","test_description":"Test the explanation analyzer with sarcastic reviews (e.g., 'Great, another broken feature', 'Love waiting 10 minutes for this to load'). Verify the explanation correctly identifies negative intent. Check that explanations mention the sarcasm/contradiction explicitly or infer negative sentiment despite positive words. Test with known sarcasm patterns and variations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic level is mandatory. Sarcasm detection is beyond deterministic rules and requires real LLM capabilities. Mocking would always return correct sarcasm detection, hiding real LLM failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Both outputs (score and explanation) are returned together in a single response, with the explanation referencing the same sentiment direction as the score.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure has two dimensions: (1) structural—both outputs present in response, and (2) semantic—explanation matches sentiment direction. A real failure occurs when explanation contradicts the score (e.g., score=negative but explanation talks positive, or vice versa). Integration-level testing with mocked outputs would always show consistency (you control both mocks). But with real LLM explanations and keyword-based sentiment, they may contradict (e.g., keyword analyzer says positive due to surface words, LLM explanation says negative due to sarcasm). Only testing with real LLM outputs catches this subtle inconsistency failure.","test_description":"Test the full API response with diverse reviews. Verify: (1) response contains both score and explanation fields, (2) explanation text mentions/references the sentiment direction of the score (negative sentiment explanation should discuss problems; positive should discuss benefits), (3) there is no contradiction between score and explanation. Use real LLM calls, not mocks. Test edge cases: sarcasm, mixed signals, neutral reviews.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic level is necessary to catch inconsistency failures. Integration testing with mocked LLM explanations would hide real contradictions that occur when the deterministic sentiment analyzer and real LLM diverge on sarcasm or nuance.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13568,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13568},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_